< text>
My first experience with putting cats into a 'kitty hotel'. Everyone was quite friendly and accommodating on drop-off and pick-up. Cats were happy and healthy when we picked them up.
Areas of improvement - (1) When I called to check up on the cats, the person who I spoke to seemed put-off? by my questions about if my cats were ok. That felt odd. (2) There is no mention of price on their website, nor was it mentioned when I dropped off my cats. You can imagine my shock when I picked up my cats and had a bill of over $1400. (3) For that kind of high cost, daily updates on how my cats are, plus some photos, would make me feel better about the high cost for their services. (4) Suggest a contract with pricing and expectations upon dropping off pets, so there's no big surprises at the end.
To end on a good note - I discovered they were taking in evacuation animals that owners didn't have the ability to keep with them -- FOR NO COST. I thought that was very cool <3</text>

<Rating>1<//Rating><Review>NOT WORTH THE MONEY FOR BOARDING!

I am NOT an overprotective dog owner, or a hard person to please...BUT...I paid over 300 dollars to board my little dog for a week, and was extremely disappointed at what that 300 dollars got me.

It was our 1st time using B&B and I was not informed of how any of it worked and if I could access any photo or video of my dog during the week or VIP treatment/rooms (which I saw online) I asked about alIergy meds being given and treats being given (bone) when he is in a crate at least once during the week. I also brought a small bed and blanket so he could have the smell of home, but was told he couldn't have either do to the fact that they will lose it. (understandable with the high volume of dogs coming and going.)

It was a TAG and GO process. IN quick - OUT quick.

On my arrival I was not told about the weeks events, or how anything went. Even after asking the Front Desk Gal, she pawned me off on the next person who then didn't give me any information besides "fine". Upon getting home I looked through his bag to find pieces of paper stapled to almost everything, with the days of the week on them. Nothing was marked on anything! NO meds were given, and not one of his treats (bones) had been opened. Word to the wise in any customer service business, if you are going to use those you should fill them out. He has had all the proper shots up to date, and has seemed "off" since we brought him home. He just hasn't seemed like the dog we dropped off at B&B.

I read reviews, the place was new seemed pretty nice, but was beyond disappointed with the overall service. They seem to be better at grooming then boarding, and I will tell people to go else where for boarding. Bummer.</Review>< pics>

<Rating>5</Rating><Text>There is no way to review a church based on traditional parameters since it's mostly related to your faith and belief and your longing for that particular place of worship. That's why we have places where people go more than others for worship and getting their wishes fulfilled. I will try and talk about some peripheral things about this place though.

Plenty of parking space since it also has a school. I love the coffee and the donuts here. The sermons from the parish priest is very relatable and informal. Very prompt in their publications. So many charity activities going on every week which in turn gives you lots of opportunities to contribute to the society and lastly, awesome people. I always attend the 8 am mass and love going to this place. May God bless you!<//Text><pictures>None<//pictures>< Response>

<rating>5</rating><review>A beautiful church in a great friendly community. The mass is always beautiful and homilies are relevant.

Very holy church dedicated to St. Jude, the patron saint of all that's impossible. There is an outdoor grotto for prayers. They also have a Catholic school.

<rate>5</rate>< review>
My sister, parents and I have been attending mass at this parish for the past 20 years. Whether you have lived in Conejo Valley and been a parishioner here for 20+ years or you have recently moved here from out of state and just started attending mass here, St. Jude is very warm and welcoming to all who enter its doors. The pastor, Fr. Jim Stehly, is one of the kindest and most compassionate people who goes above and beyond to make all feel at home when they are here. I am very proud to be involved in their Loaves and Fishes Ministry which helps the less fortunate in both LA and Ventura Counties. Getting involved in one of the ministries here is a great way to meet great people.</review>

Love taking the Expo Line, this has truly opened up new opportunities for the City of Los Angeles.  It is very reasonable to travel $1.75/each way and there is a discount for seniors! <user>101132909266086505193<//user>< user_name>
Dave Chung<//user_name>
<time>1444502100020</time><rating>4</rating><Text>As the current end point for western end of the Expo line, the Culver City station is a nice "flag ship" for what a big station can be like on the light rail. There's a lot  of surface parking for a non-event day. It feels safe. And it's pretty easy for newcomers to figure out what's going on.

That being said, there is not even close to enough parking spots in this lot to support major events. When there is a USC football game, this parking lot gets absurdly full. There isn't enough convenient street parking nearby (and it sucks for the nearby residents), so people who are planning to take the train downtown are often left circling and praying that a spot opens up.

Especially as the line expands to Santa Monica and usage grows over the next year, this really needs to be more than just a surface level lot. While the station is pretty nice, it was really poor planning on the city's part to not make this a multi-level parking structure. Every time that a first-time rider gets turned away at the parking lot is another person who will never try to ride metro again.<//Text>< pics>

< text>
It Is About Time!

Los Angeles used to have their very own Train System called the Los Angeles Railway (also known as Yellow Cars, LARy, and later Los Angeles Transit Lines) was a system of streetcars that operated in central Los Angeles, California, and the immediate surrounding neighborhoods between 1901 and 1963. Except for two short, 2 ft 6 in (762 mm) narrow gauge[1][2] funicular railways named Angels Flight and Court Flight, it operated on 3 ft 6 in (1,067 mm) narrow gauge tracks. The company carried many more passengers than the Pacific Electric Railway's 'Red Cars' which served a larger area of Los Angeles. The two companies shared some dual gauge 3 ft 6 in (1,067 mm) / 4 ft 8 1‚ÅÑ2 in (1,435 mm) standard gauge track along Hawthorne Boulevard, on Main Street and on 4th Street.

Today, they have the Expo Line which now goes from downtown los angeles towards santa monica beach and long beach and hollywood up to north hollywood, stretching its' way to pasadena all the way to azusa and citrus college.

In addition, there are other train lines to and the system just keeps on getting better and better.

Currently, they are working on the crenshaw line which will take you by train close to the airport and then you just get a shuttle bus from there.

They are also working on the purple line which will take you to beverly hills, century city and ucla.

Amazing!

I think this system will serve its' people well!

In my photos, you will see me getting on the train to go from santa monica back towards los angeles.

I hope you will board their expo line train the next time that you are trying to get somewhere like I did.

Thank you.

Sincerely yours,

Howard  Paul Shore
Metro Expo Line Customer And Rider

/HPS< /text>

< Text>
This is a sad but uber happy review. I have had my storage at this location since 2008! I have been a tenant for 11 yrs! Do you know how long that is. I have been here through 3 name changes and company take overs. I met Roger a long time ago. I had storage because I fell on hard times and wanted to keep my belongings in the area as a mental picture that I would be back. Well it happened and I got my own condo Monday. I closed my storage Thursday and got a chance to say goodbye to Roger. I was excited about my new place and finally clearing out my storage but sad because this guy has been apart of my life for so long. He had my back as the protector of my belongings and he was so gracious in allowing me to remain there. I will never forget when fires rocked our area last year and I was so worried about my belongings because I could not reach Roger for almost 5 days. When I finally talked  to him I was relieved and he said "We are ok!" He said we meaning my belongings and him. That meant we were in this together! I hate late fees but when I was late Roger was always understanding! Now I still had to pay! But he was so helpful, encouraging and solid. What a great guy and it seems like I am losing a family member. Thank you Roger for holding down the fort and looking out for me all these years. What a great guy and I am blessed to have been in communication with a guy like that!< /Text>

<username>Angie Wiseman</username><time>1480290278525</time>< Rating>
5<//Rating>
<Text>One thing people may not realize about running a mundane storage facility errand, is that it may in fact be the case that the storage locker hasn't been opened in years. Likely, the items inside hold some value, if not at least some sentimental value. Opening an old locker may mean an emotional ride that you hadn't prepared for. Today, I decided to clear out my tiny locker filled with banker boxes holding old photos : office items and college papers. There was zero anticipation of any kind of an emotional reaction whatsoever and that's why I was caught off guard to feel the feelings I was feeling; reminiscing and also realizing that time goes by so quickly these days! LIFE goes by!

The kindness of the assistant manager, Serena Canion, truly helped me feel comfortable and calm about clearing out my locker. Not only had I lost my key by this point, but I had also not had enough room in my car to empty everything out. She had broken off my lock, lent me a new lock to close the locker up, and also offered -- most importantly-- her warmth. Aside from her personal touch of kindness, she was extremely well informed about the brand and it's inner workings. I was very impressed with her knowledge, pride of working for Life Storage, and also her very organized and thorough paperwork.. I felt safe with her.

Finding this type of welcome at an institutional storage locker facility does not go unrecognized. In a completely indirect way, Serena's confidence, care, warmth, and service held me together and reminded me that good people matter and need to be valued. This is a public review to recognize her humanity and also to give Life Storage a high 5 with their color selection and upbeat feel with their new branding strategy! It worked for me!

Thanks Life Storage for hiring just that perfect individual to host the clients who may be using the facilities for a variety of life reasons. I'd love to see her promoted.< /Text>< Pictures>

But when we went there our latch/lock was all screwed up & hard to open which means someone had all the time to work on breaking in. We saw that 4 TV's, PlayStation, printer, 3 large bags of my clothes were stolen among other things. They have people living on the facility. Conveniently NO CAMERAS on the aisle where my things were stolen. This is either an inside job or the people living in their units. Front office workers encourage new customers to give positive reviews on the website but when I went there on the day I found out what was stolen there were two customers upset that there things were stolen as well with no footage. It took 4 hours for Pomona PD to show up for us to get a report & for him to say 'this happens here all the time'. Had I known this place was this poorly secured I would not have gone here OR I would have purchased better insurance because they sure don't care about nothing but your monthly payment. You're supposed to do your part but they are horrible at doing their part. They should let you know from your 1st day there to purchase the highest insurance because things are stolen from there a lot and that people live in their units. Call back was too slow from the district manager Rick Jansen and now I'm over talking to him. I will pursue further action to recover what was stolen from this essentially open to the public to steal your things...Public Storage.< /Review>

< review>
I happen to stop in on this place from a day trip with kids playing in the Tahoe snow all day. Kids are always picky eaters to start with. We saw a couple of pizza joints along the road heading up earlier in the day and we felt it wasn‚Äôt going to be a problem feeding the troops on the way back. Sadly I was mistaken and found that the pizza places were closed??? It was a bit disappointing and we decided to wait till Elk Grove to stop off along the way back to home. As a last ditch effort we looked for pizza eateries along hwy 50 as we‚Äôre coming down the road. The name Pizza Plus stood out being that we love the Ripon Pizza Plus. We decided to make a pitstop and check it out. I honestly didn‚Äôt read reviews or really how far off the main hwy they were located at being that it looked like it wasn‚Äôt too far. I ordered a Lg.pepperoni, Sm. Hawaiian, and Med.Rockin Combo for 9 people. The gang devoured all the pies down to one last small slice. The crust was so crispy and had the all so desirable fresh bread from the oven smell and taste. Just the right amount of fresh toppings that made for a perfect pizza pie. Everyone raved at how delicious the pizza was, and how it was worth the small detour. We have definitely found a new go to stop when next we‚Äôre nearby by. The staff was very friendly which also made for an enjoyable experience. Looking forward to enjoying some pizza indoors at this place to try out other goodies on their menu. Great Job Placerville Pizza Plus.<//review>

<Resp>None< /Resp><Text>Mmmm! This pizza is sooo good! My fiance and I have been trying various pizza places in Pasadena to find our favorite and I think we've finally found our go-to spot.

We ordered two personal 12" pizzas - the pear & gorgonzola and the standard pizza - via their online ordering system, Clover, and picked them up to eat at home. Both were amazingly delicious! I first tried the standard pizza which has pepperoni and mozzarella on it. <time>1467068970555<//time><Rate>5< /Rate><Review>I LOVE THIS PLACE this is a MUST visit when you are in Azusa.

The food is taste GREAT, generous portions, the service is fantastic.  This is the difference of a FAMILY OWNED Business and a Corporate one.  Each staff member works as a seamless team, making sure your dining experience is a good one.

We recently held an event for a movie documentary / shoot with about 50 Cyclists.  We called the owners let them know what we had in mind, and they accommodated us.  They normally close at 8pm on Tuesday Night, but they stood open for us.

We have been there several times, when they are busy and when they are not - You get the same level of dedicated service, everyone is hustling to make sure you are taken care of.  I support family owned business because their livelihood depends on it, However it is a now brainer to come back here when the food is delicious and the service is good.

<review>I stopped in here to see what it was all about. I am a big fan of Bronx pizza and I want to see how this would compare. I must say I am a fan of this restaurant. I will not go as far as to say it is the same as Bronx pizza because this is more of a Long Island style. The sauce is great the crust is great and the toppings are of a high quality. I like the fact that they have regular Italian style thin crust pizza as well as Sicilian pizza. The white stone is good the pepperoni mushroom was excellent and I also like the fact that they have garlic powder, parmesan as well and red chili flakes for you to put on your pizza. When I ordered my slice the employees here notice that the pizza was already  a little old so they made me fresh slices. This really shows the type of customer service that is needed in any service industry. I would recommend this pizza place and I will be back. The lady that was working at the front Ashley was very nice and very helpful. The gentleman that was cooking the pizzas name was Adrian he was the one that noticed that the pizza that they were going to serve me was a bit old so they made fresh ones. That to me shows the attention to detail that is needed. I am very happy with the service.<//review><Pictures>None</Pictures>< Resp>

I went there for my first vaccine shot this morning. This is the best large vaccination site in Santa Clara county. Very efficient. Lines move rapidly. Check ins are quick and easy. I moved directly to the inoculation station. Valley medical administers the vaccine with a 2 cm needle. I didn't feel even a poke. Perfect vaccination.
I recommend this site for their organized effort. I had no side effects.</Text>

< review>
A sad fair, the organizers utterly failed and I don‚Äôt even want to give 1 star, but I‚Äôm forced otherwise I can‚Äôt post this.
Santa Clara County is one of the most profitable counties in California because we are ground zero for the high tech industry, such as Google. I/we went to the fair last night and was shocked by the lack of actual county representation. The ‚ÄòCounty Fair‚Äô should show case the bests of the county.

The fair is literally the worst fair I had ever been to in my life, we were there Friday from 6-8pm. We left out of sheer boredom.

1.) The main entrance advertisement sign that‚Äôs supposed to be facing the street is actually backwards, so u don‚Äôt know what‚Äôs even going on in there if u drive by.
2.) Stage highlights: square dancing & Vietnam dancers - this was the highlights. That‚Äôs it for Friday Night.
3.) The approximately 10k sq ft art building had no climate control, so it was really hot and had stale air - not a single person in the art building.
4.) The location is the area where 99% crime and murders happens in Santa Clara County. Why is this the location for the County Fair? That makes no sense at all.
5.) The sheep and rabbits were cool, but then there were several cages with fake chickens in the FFA/4H chicken area. Why would we want to see fake animals in the live animal area?

As far as the rides, etc. it reminded me of being in a fly by night cheap carnival.

I conclude, I/we will never go back it‚Äôs just not a true snapshot representation of beautiful Santa Clara.< /review>

<Rating>1</Rating><text>I'm 3 years new to the area having moved down from the NW.  I was really looking forward to taking in a local fair having not been able to the last couple of years. Went 8/2/15 and arrived about 20 minutes early thinking that it had opened at 10am - didn't open till 11am.  What an experience.  Security lined women up in one line and men in another in front of the gate. I've never seen this done before in America. I felt like I was in a Nazi camp.  I even saw small children cry because there dad had to go in the men's line nowhere near his family like the rest of us.  This is supposed to be a family event! Unheard of!  This fair is VERY small and I knew that, but the lack of participation by the community as witnessed by the incredibly small displays in photography, art, food, and vendors and everything else you would expect in a fair made this place worthless.  The only thing that was enjoyable was the lack of crowds. Obviously the locals have been here before and know not to come back.<//text><pictures>None<//pictures>< Resp>

< Review>
Good to have the faire back.  Enjoyed the pepper steak and the Phillies steak.  The smoked turkey leg was good and worth the price.  Don't bother with the foot long corn dog.  Definitely not worth the price.  The corn bread covering the skinniest hot dog I have ever seen was tough!  The kids enjoyed it though.  They liked seeing the small animals as the large animal barn was closed.  Enjoyed the sea lion exhibit for both the show and the valuable information.  They rode  the ponies, petted the animals and had a great time on the bungee jump.  Spent a great deal of time and energy on the walk on water attraction. They enjoyed the carnival rides and went on some some more than once.  They played the games and were treated well by all the people working the rides and games.  It was a good time had by all.  The kids were exhausted at the end of the day!< /Review>

We went to see Train Show.  The parking was confusing as there was no sign pointing to Train Show parking lot.  We got there early so the parking lot looked empty/closed.  Figured it out though.  The model railroad setups were nice with some of them having push button controls for kids to control small details.  At least half the floor was shops selling pricey trains and landscapes and figures.  Looked like good stuff for the otaku crowd.  Too fancy for nubes.  Outside was a bounce house and ride on train ride (must buy tickets).

Tickets were $10 for adults and kids free.  A search will find a $1 off coupon code.  Parking was $10.<//Review>

Every time im there i have an experience not worth going back. I dont even want to comment because of bad memories but i will.
